Network Fundamentals: Building a Simple LAN with a Layer 2 Switch

📌 Project Overview
This project demonstrates a basic Local Area Network (LAN) using a Cisco Catalyst 2960 Switch. The objective is to contrast the intelligent forwarding behavior of a Switch against the broadcast nature of a Hub, focusing on Unicast communication and the MAC Address Table.

🛠️ Technologies Used
Cisco Packet Tracer 8.x
Hardware: Cisco 2960 Series Switch
Networking Concepts: Layer 2 Switching, Ethernet, MAC Addresses, ICMP.

🛰️ Topology Details
Two workstations connected to a central switch via Copper Straight-Through cables:
PC0: 192.168.1.10 /24
PC1: 192.168.1.11 /24
Interconnect: FastEthernet0/1 and FastEthernet0/2

🚀 Lab Objectives
Switch Deployment: Replaced the Hub with a 24-port Intelligent Switch (2960).
Addressing: Assigned static IP addresses within the same subnet to ensure local reachability.
Connectivity Test: Executed a ping command from PC0 to PC1.
Traffic Analysis: Used Simulation Mode to observe how the Switch handles frames compared to a Hub.

🔍 Key Observations (Switch vs. Hub)
Unlike the previous Hub exercise, the following improvements were noted:
Micro-Segmentation: The Switch created a dedicated path between PC0 and PC1.
Unicast Delivery: After the initial ARP (Address Resolution Protocol) request, the ICMP packet was sent only to the intended destination. No other ports received the data.
MAC Address Table: By accessing the Switch CLI and running show mac-address-table, I verified that the switch "learned" which device was on which port, allowing for efficient frame switching.
Full Duplex: The Switch allows for simultaneous two-way communication, eliminating the collision issues found in Hub-based networks.

